# Burst analysis

The analysis is tricky because there are only 2 replicates. Comparing male AA1 vs male CN2 is valid but is specific to these replicates. To generalize, would need to take means of replicates. But then we have only n = 2! Also, sex also adds unwarrented df because it really is a random variable with two groups.

```{r import}
subfolder <- "burst speed/simons-walker "
filename <- "Wind Tunnel minus days>6.xlsx"
in_path <- here(data_folder, subfolder, filename)

simons <- read_xlsx(in_path) |>
  clean_names() |>
  data.table()

simons[, id := .I]
simons[, treatment := factor(treatment, levels = c("CN", "AA"))]
simons[, sex := factor(sex, levels = c("M", "F"))]
simons[, line := paste(treatment, line) |>
       factor(levels = c("CN 1", "CN 2", "AA 1", "AA 2"))]

```


